**Netflix at $89: The Case for 104% Upside as Margins Finally Catch the Gro=
wth**

****

Netflix (NASDAQ: NFLX) built the dominant global streaming platform by movi=
ng faster than every traditional media company and spending more aggressive=
ly than every technology competitor that tried to follow. The company now r=
eaches over 300 million paid memberships across more than 190 countries, a =
scale that no rival has come close to matching across the full breadth of i=
ts international footprint. Revenue has compounded at nearly 21% annually o=
ver the past decade, and the margin profile has transformed from breakeven =
to genuinely exceptional as the fixed cost of content gets spread across an=
 ever-larger subscriber base.

The competitive position is harder to replicate than the subscriber count a=
lone suggests. Netflix has spent two decades building a content library, re=
commendation engine, and production infrastructure that functions as a sing=
le integrated system. The algorithm learns from the viewing behavior of hun=
dreds of millions of users to surface the right content at the right moment=
, which reduces churn and increases the perceived value of the subscription=
 in ways that are invisible in any single financial metric. No new entrant =
can buy that data advantage. It compounds only with time and scale.

The margin story is the most important financial development of the past fi=
ve years. Net income margins have expanded from effectively zero a decade a=
go to 22% in the trailing year, with the forward model projecting further e=
xpansion toward 33% as revenue grows faster than the content and technology=
 cost base beneath it. That trajectory is not a function of cutting investm=
ent. Netflix continues to spend heavily on content. It is a function of ope=
rating leverage at a scale the business has only recently reached.

https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D104673&tid=3D2661077=20

The growth debate has shifted from subscriber additions to revenue per user=
. The ad-supported tier launched in 2022 and has since become a meaningful =
part of the mix, opening a monetization layer that the subscription-only mo=
del could never access. Live events, including NFL games and high-profile b=
oxing matches, are extending the platform's relevance beyond on-demand view=
ing and into the kind of appointment television that commands premium adver=
tising rates. International markets, particularly in Asia and Latin America=
, continue to add subscribers at a pace that keeps the top-line growing eve=
n as North America matures.

Under mid-case assumptions in the model above, Netflix could deliver roughl=
y 104% total upside through year-end 2030, implying approximately 16.7% ann=
ualized returns from a current price of $89.33. That would put the stock at=
 a target price of $182.56, driven by continued subscriber and revenue per =
user growth, margin expansion as the advertising business scales, and a con=
tent investment cycle that begins to moderate relative to revenue.

The model assumes revenue growing at roughly 9.6% annually through 2035 und=
er the mid case, with net income margins expanding toward 33%. EPS is proje=
cted to grow at a 14.7% CAGR over that period, reflecting the combination o=
f revenue compounding and the natural operating leverage of a platform busi=
ness where incremental subscribers generate revenue with minimal incrementa=
l cost.

Competition remains the most persistent risk, though its shape has changed.=
 Disney, Warner Bros.

Discovery, and Amazon continue investing in streaming content, and any sust=
ained acceleration in their spending could force Netflix to respond in kind=
. Password sharing monetization has already been largely captured, which me=
ans the next leg of subscriber growth depends on winning new households rat=
her than converting existing ones. A broader pullback in advertising spendi=
ng would also slow the ad tier ramp at a moment when that business is still=
 building toward its potential.

Netflix is one of the cleaner compounders in the consumer technology space,=
 with a business model that is generating real earnings, expanding margins,=
 and throwing off increasing amounts of free cash flow as capital intensity=
 moderates. The stock's recent decline from its highs reflects valuation re=
calibration more than any deterioration in the underlying business, and the=
 model suggests the current price offers a reasonable entry point for inves=
tors with a multi-year time horizon.

